{"text": "The second term in Eq. (17) has an effective mass and we assume m(\u2212x) = \u2212m(x) is a\n\nspatially varying mass term that changes sign at x = 0 (the location of the domain wall).\n\nWe now assume that the quasiparticle operator\n\nq\u2020 =\n\nZ\n\ndx [\u03c61(x)f \u2020\n\n1(x) + \u03c62(x)f \u2020\n\n2(x)]\n\n(18)\n\nsatisfies the operator equation,\n\n[H1\n\nD, q\u2020] = \u03b5q\u2020.\n\n(19)\n\nComputing the commutator in Eq. 19 we find the following Dirac equation for the two-\n\ncomponent wave function \u03c6T(x) = (\u03c61(x), \u03c62(x)):\n\n\u2212ivF\u03c3y\u2202x\u03c6(x) + \u03c3zm(x)\u03c6(x) = \u03b5\u03c6(x).\n\n(20)\n\nFirst we note that because \u03c3y anticommutes with \u03c3x and \u03c3z, the first quantized Hamiltonian\n\nH1\n\nD = \u2212ivF\u03c3y\u2202x + \u03c3zm(x) anticommutes with \u03c3x, {H1\n\nD, \u03c3x} = 0.\n\nThen, if \u03c6(x) is an\n\neigenfunction of H1\n\nD with eigenvalue \u03b5, H1\n\nD\u03c3y\u03c6(x) = \u2212\u03c3yH1\n\nD\u03c6(x) = \u2212\u03b5\u03c3y\u03c6(x), i.e., \u03c3y\u03c6(x) is\n\nalso an eigenfunction of H1\n\nD with eigenvalue \u2212\u03b5. As a result, the \u03b5 = 0 solutions of Eq. (20)\n\ncan be made a simultaneous eigenstate of H1\n\nD and \u03c3x. Let \u03c60(x) denote such a solution and\n\n\u03c3x\u03c60(x) = \u03bb\u03c60(x).\n\n(21)\n\nSetting \u03b5 = 0 and left-multiplying Eq. (20) by i\u03c3z we obtain\n\n\u2202x\u03c60(x) = \u03bb\n\nvF\n\nm(x)\u03c60(x),\n\nwhich implies\n\n\u03c60(x) = e\n\n\u03bb\n\nvF\n\nR x\n\n0 m(x\u2032)dx\u2032\u03c60(0).\n\n(22)\n\nFor m(x) = \u00b1sign(x) m(x) , Eq. (22) is a normalizable function for \u03bb = \u22131. In this way\n\nwe have now proven that for a sign change of m(x) (i.e. a mass domain wall) there is a\n\nsingle zero energy eigenvalue of the one-dimensional Dirac Hamiltonian with a wave function\n\nthat is exponentially localized away from the mass domain wall. Note that, the zero energy\n\nsolution is robust against variations in the mass distribution function m(x), as long as there\n\n10\n\nis a change of sign of the mass term at some value of x. The normalizable zero-energy\n\nsolution exists if\n\nm(x) = \u2212m1\n\nif\n\nx < 0\n\n= +m2\n\nif\n\nx > 0\n\n(23)\n\nwith m1, m2 > 0. In particular, the solution exists even if the mass on the right hand side\n\nof the domain wall diverges m2 \u2192\u221e.", "embedding": [0.0036735944, -0.01207251, 0.019255111, 0.013849809, 0.008735993, -0.042059217, -0.0059516, -0.0014754818, -0.062372267, 0.0679641, 0.04885752, 0.017379671, -0.016344734, -0.030904956, -0.03729072, 0.045639735, -0.01434105, -0.009872639, -0.06961757, 0.029253133, 0.0570811, 0.0068435324, -0.042046167, -0.0063272174, -0.029957846, 0.018628322, 0.041493338, 0.02573672, 0.05436905, 0.04488772, 0.05803148, -0.0069851135, 0.03944026, -0.024623523, -0.009281025, 0.017284678, -0.007521779, -0.02942227, 0.062970914, -0.018197449, 0.052235533, -0.008092028, 0.003699759, -0.0042774808, -0.043935895, -0.01581348, -0.028028825, 0.011810303, -0.036268994, -0.052690838, -0.0013178786, 0.0010176983, 0.036121972, -0.020662429, -0.017120553, -0.025289191, 0.00747588, 0.008487451, -0.018413473, -0.009529656, 0.0039146934, 0.0004314146, -0.006068429, -0.060302127, 0.005501548, 0.032310076, -0.004652187, 0.0728505, 0.0050143893, -0.03996477, 0.006949016, 0.006371791, -0.011641111, 0.0300259, -0.02699901, 0.039019305, -0.023329675, -0.07496574, -0.060008407, -0.0018709885, -0.043203805, -0.017202936, -0.012285272, 0.039576337, -0.005060597, 0.016068215, 0.004548129, -0.0347584, -0.0011675092, 0.018082684, 0.035700154, 0.04132725, -0.014307091, 1.2847879e-05, 0.05287722, 0.05643808, 0.017216573, 0.039998483, 0.024570266, -0.0042680204, 0.0069316365, 0.041722164, -0.031069193, 0.05674246, -0.025287587, 0.04637699, -0.022512725, 0.035809368, -0.027275722, -0.028917182, 0.020011604, -0.024894224, 0.021285973, 0.012357786, 0.0008045184, 0.024409909, 0.02120323, -0.0054016183, -0.059307903, -0.033343837, -0.006